b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\r\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\r\n<workbook_page xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/"\r\n\txmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\r\n\txmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\r\n\txmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\r\n\txmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/" id="p2_chemical">\r\n\t<head>\r\n\t\t<title>Chemical Stoichiometry and Gases</title>\r\n\t\t<objref idref="stoich_gas"/>\r\n\t\t<objref idref="stoich_gas2"/>\r\n\t</head>\r\n\t<body>\r\n\t\t<section>\r\n\t\t\t<title>Avogadro\xe2\x80\x99s Law Revisited</title>\r\n\t\t\t<body>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="aa22a8dcc6f7f43eebf2a59afd1cabd39"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="ae6cb7268a804abeb5a5962ae3ca5815">Sometimes we can take advantage of a\r\n\t\t\t\t\tsimplifying feature of the stoichiometry of gases that solids and solutions do\r\n\t\t\t\t\tnot exhibit: All gases that show ideal behavior contain the same number of\r\n\t\t\t\t\tmolecules in the same volume (at the same temperature and pressure). Thus, the\r\n\t\t\t\t\tratios of volumes of gases involved in a chemical reaction are given by the\r\n\t\t\t\t\tcoefficients in the equation for the reaction, provided that the gas volumes are\r\n\t\t\t\t\tmeasured at the same temperature and pressure.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="aaa8690fbd47d43c5b127687814a68e61"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="b28d89a35ae34d69a25829e7fc810171"> We can extend Avogadro\xe2\x80\x99s law (that the\r\n\t\t\t\t\tvolume of a gas is directly proportional to the number of moles of the gas) to\r\n\t\t\t\t\tchemical reactions with gases: Gases combine, or react, in definite and simple\r\n\t\t\t\t\tproportions by volume, provided that all gas volumes are measured at the same\r\n\t\t\t\t\ttemperature and pressure. For example, since nitrogen and hydrogen gases react\r\n\t\t\t\t\tto produce ammonia gas according to N<sub>2</sub> (g) + 3 H<sub>2</sub> (g) \xe2\x9f\xb6 2\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tNH<sub>3</sub> (g), a given volume of nitrogen gas reacts with three times\r\n\t\t\t\t\tthat volume of hydrogen gas to produce two times that volume of ammonia gas, if\r\n\t\t\t\t\tpressure and temperature remain constant. </p>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="aeea30462fdcf40c389f436debd5879cd"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<!--<section>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<title>Slide Show</title>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<body><iframe src="https://h5p.org/h5p/embed/224929" width="750" height="443"/></body>\r\n\t\t\t\t</section>-->\r\n\r\n\t\t\t\t<section>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<title>Slide Show</title>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<body>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>Press "NEXT" to advance slide show.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<wb:inline idref="gas_stp_ss"></wb:inline>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</body>\r\n\t\t\t\t</section>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t\t<example>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aa11bea0da3404314a03bedf75da4af74"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="e622ef6ac47549748665b4e92bf70cc8"> Propane, C<sub>3</sub>H<sub>8</sub>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t(g), is used in gas grills to provide the heat for cooking. What volume of\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\tO<sub>2</sub> (g) measured at 25 \xc2\xb0C and 760 torr is required to react\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\twith 2.7 L of propane measured under the same conditions of temperature and\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tpressure? Assume that the propane undergoes complete combustion. </p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="afd946f39e8bb4e4a984589e19c26e262"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ab7924abbf3247378d6e135975af48c8"> The ratio of the volumes of\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\tC<sub>3</sub>H <sub>8</sub> and O<sub>2</sub> will be equal to the ratio\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tof their coefficients in the balanced equation for the reaction: </p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aad308a931abe467d81d72ac0ba1b0d30"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t <formula>C<sub>3</sub>H<sub>8</sub>(g) + 5\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tO<sub>2</sub>(g) \xe2\x86\x92 3 CO<sub>2</sub>(g) + 4 H<sub>2</sub>O(l)</formula> \r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ae3af7c702a924c79bdb7286f3a49d107"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="dd336c44639e43ae8589932b043fef42"> From the equation, we see that one\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tvolume of C<sub>3</sub>H<sub>8</sub> will react with five volumes of O<sub>2</sub> : </p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ab62b03ef13ec4816b38519e9ff76c2cb"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ff65b67718ad4c71a4ff812a8360180f">$$\\require{cancel} 2.7\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\\cancel{\\mathrm{L\\ C_3H_8}} \\times \\frac{5 \\mathrm{L\\ O_2}}{1\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\\cancel{\\mathrm{L\\ C_3H_8}}} = 13.5 \\mathrm{L\\ O_2}$$</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ad92cc00ca20245f48353d8a39c00d368"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="a3dc562b0bb0492a81384cafe34b4c12"> A volume of 13.5 L of O<sub>2</sub>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\twill be required to react with 2.7 L of C<sub>3</sub>H<sub>8</sub> . </p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</example>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="ae362977454234d9790e7ec1ac4ffe2c4"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="de118994d1194d4f94887b77224f89d9"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<wb:inline idref="chemstoich_lbd1d15d6dcc8a914d00bf367d4d5fd112a5"\r\n\t\t\t\t\tpurpose="learnbydoing"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="ace803add5e1f430ca258a6a4259cbdb4"/>\r\n\t\t\t</body>\r\n\t\t</section>\r\n\t\t<section>\r\n\t\t\t<title>Combining Stoichiometry and Gas Laws</title>\r\n\t\t\t<body>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="afec7cb59f5374e47a8bc7f12ed57f8ca"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="e1fa2d89b132408dbd3ecbee779b53f0">Not all reactions involving gases take\r\n\t\t\t\t\tplace at STP or under constant conditions. In such cases, it may be necessary to\r\n\t\t\t\t\tcombine stoichiometry techniques with gas laws. Let&apos;s take a look at some\r\n\t\t\t\t\tsuch problems.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t<example>\r\n\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aecbbd7c328dd4ccebb2cfbe545c50dff"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="e1388e4668b546e38ae42544494fcd81">What volume of hydrogen at 27 \xc2\xb0C and\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t723 torr may be prepared by the reaction of 8.88 g of gallium with an excess\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tof hydrochloric acid?</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aea3c267b3b5f4a978dc4c2732d0c1f80"/>\r\n\t\t\t<formula> 2 Ga(s) + 6 HCl(aq) \xe2\x9f\xb6 2 GaCl<sub>3</sub> (aq) + 3H<sub>2</sub>(g) </formula>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ac869d7c513c74b01962c96ca27822449"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="b74ed804e742465f8f4e93aeb06143ea">Note that in a similar problem above we\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tused the molar volume of a gas (22.4 L) to make this calculation. This will\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tnot work here because the reaction does not occur at STP.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ad0d74750ef344376b0a494f901a93467"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ab28a9ecb9e2410f87ddb0ef0c40e0f0"> To convert from mass of gallium to\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tvolume of H<sub>2</sub> (g) we will follow a similar process initially to\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tfind the mol of H<sub>2</sub> (g) produced. Then apply the ideal gas\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tequation to find the volume of H<sub>2</sub> (g) at the given temperature\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tand pressure. The steps of the process are seen below: </p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ad774287da0344b6ab14975f357de68d5"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t <formula>g Ga \xe2\x86\x92 mol Ga \xe2\x86\x92 mol H <sub>2</sub> \xe2\x86\x92 L\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tH<sub>2</sub> (Ideal Gas Law) </formula>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="adb98a51287dc4db586f9cf5ed8d6685d"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="b2de25c3e97c4eb8b2133d6bbf5c7efe"> Convert from g Ga to mol H\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<sub>2</sub> using stoichiometry. </p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ac7e76ad1ba3349eab852c06ec675873a"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="a976e55b0f4948fea7662ad5113d3ba4">$$\\require{cancel} 8.88\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\\cancel{\\mathrm{g\\ Ga}} \\times \\frac{1 \\cancel{\\mathrm{mol\\ Ga}}}{69.72\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\\cancel{\\mathrm{g\\ Ga}}} \\times \\frac{3 \\mathrm{mol\\ H_2}}{2\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol\\ Ga}}} = 0.191 \\mathrm{mol H_2}$$</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aaf3cfeda7c234be187b5360574717f8d"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="fd14c18389c045bd8f97001c0b8c0ca1"> Now apply the ideal gas law to\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\tcalculate the volume of H <sub>2</sub> . </p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="abb6186ad6ef645889ec42a601c3cba45"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p id="d2a64da94f114c92a21df36a540ce8e3">$$\\require{cancel} V_{\\mathrm{H_2}} =\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t{\\left(\\frac{nRt}{P}\\right)}_{H_2} = \\frac{0.191 \\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}}\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\\times 0.08206 \\cancel{\\mathrm{atm}}\\ \\mathrm{L}\\ \\cancel{\\mathrm{mol^{-1}}}\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\\cancel{\\mathrm{K^{-1}}} \\times 300 \\cancel{\\mathrm{K}}}{0.951\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\\cancel{\\mathrm{atm}}} = 4.94 \\mathrm{L\\ H_2}$$</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</example>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="ad9c2cc0fbd3d4861a1787baaf1d88bbc"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<!--<section>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<title>Interactive Example</title>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<body><iframe src="https://h5p.org/h5p/embed/224920" width="750" height="443"/></body>\r\n\t\t\t\t</section>-->\r\n\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t<section>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<title>Interactive Example</title>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<body>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>Press "NEXT" to advance the slides.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<wb:inline idref="gas_stoich_ie"></wb:inline>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</body>\r\n\t\t\t\t</section>\r\n\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t<wb:inline idref="gas_stoich_steps" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t<wb:inline idref="chemstoich_lbd3dba254f57a8b4c5c94e0d052499ce310"\r\n\t\t\t\t\tpurpose="learnbydoing"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t<wb:inline idref="chemstoich_digte96511b789c549c9b065aca2da48859a"\r\n\t\t\t\t\tpurpose="didigetthis"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="ae6ae04dc2cf449adabb24797a1ad9639"/>\r\n\t\t\t</body>\r\n\t\t</section>\r\n\t\t<p id="ad027573594d449ffa0661f5cb854b711"/>\r\n\t\t<p id="dc0f3fa447f04966935d396071cafff8"> Adapted from <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="http://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface" target="new"\r\n\t\t\t\tinternal="false">Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" target="new" internal="false"\r\n\t\t\t\t>Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 License</link> . </p>\r\n\t\t<p id="ab97a2eb6b7bc4ef0a851cd361a6066e1"/>\r\n\t\t<p id="fcd01a9a4efb49fc8ca2dc7b5aefd2e3"> Download for free at <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312."\r\n\t\t\t\ttarget="new" internal="false"\r\n\t\t\t\t>http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link>\r\n\t\t</p>\r\n\t</body>\r\n</workbook_page>\r\n'